{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Imaging biomarkers are defined as characteristics extracted from the images of an individual that can be objectively measured and function as indicators of a normal biological process, a disease, or a response to a therapeutic intervention.",
    "Imaging biomarkers are complementary to conventional radiological readings to detect a specific disease or lesion, to quantify its biological situation, to evaluate its progression, to stratify phenotypic abnormalities and to assess the treatment response [29,30].",
    "This connection could be necessary for the researchers to find an association between phenotype and genotype [31,32], to design and validate new imaging biomarkers, as well as to understand their biological significance, which may be a crucial point in precision medicine [33].",
    "Another important difference is the organization of data and the way they can be retrieved.",
    "Whilst a PACS can be defined patient-based, in the sense that a query is based on the search for singlepatient examinations, an imaging biobank can be defined population-based or disease-oriented as patients having a common disease are grouped and a user can query a specific study or disease [31]."
  ],
